      <h3>Team Brain &amp; Oncall Agent: Platforms Team Knowledge Layer (2026)</h3>
      <p>
        Platforms team behind 40+ apps. Two costs compound across every
        engineer, every day:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>The explanation tax.</strong> You open an AI session and paste the same wiki links, re-explain the same app, the same conventions, the same runbook. Next session, same drill. Across a team, across a year, this is an enormous tax on the most leveraged thing engineers do.</li>
        <li><strong>The wiki rot loop.</strong> The bot that comments on incoming tasks reads from the same wikis. Wikis drift, bot drifts, engineers stop trusting the bot, wikis get worse. Self-reinforcing.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        I'm building a <strong>team brain</strong> to kill both, and this is the
        project I'm most fired up about right now. A git repo of markdown that
        every team AI session pulls in automatically as <strong>shared memory</strong>.
        Not a wiki. Wikis are documents people read. <strong>The brain is the
        context the agent already has when you start typing.</strong>
      </p>
      <p>What lives in it:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Playbooks</strong> for every common operation.</li>
        <li><strong>Processes</strong> the team actually follows.</li>
        <li><strong>App details and architecture</strong> for the apps the team touches.</li>
        <li><strong>Useful commands</strong>, the tribal-knowledge one-liners that never made it into a doc.</li>
        <li><strong>Oncall details and alert history</strong>, what's fired, why, what worked.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Two skill primitives hold the system together:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Read skills</strong> that hydrate new Claude (and other-agent) sessions from the brain before the engineer types a thing. Explanation tax to zero. <strong>The case I care most about: rotating oncall.</strong> Instead of every new oncall paging the SME for every unfamiliar alert, the brain hands them the playbook on the first prompt.</li>
        <li><strong>Write skills</strong> that update the brain through deeper logic, not raw commits. Engineers are prompted at meaningful moments (closing a task, resolving an alert, finishing an incident) and the skill captures what changed in a structured way the next session can consume.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Bootstrapped both the brain and the task-comment bot off <strong>dynamic
        workflows over historic task data</strong>, so the rollout started warm,
        not cold.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The bet:</strong> people move faster. Tribal knowledge stops being
        a bottleneck, it diminishes when it lives in the brain instead of three
        people's heads. The texture matters: it feels great to hop on a new
        session and know the agent already has an idea of what you're talking
        about. The first turn isn't "let me catch you up." It's "here's what I'd
        do."
      </p>
      <p>
        And every automation the team builds on top inherits the same advantage.
        The task-comment bot was just the first; anything new the team ships,
        workflows, agents, evals, wakes up with a current knowledge base, not a
        stale one.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Status:</strong> rolling out across the team.
      </p>

